#week-title("Four", "Lunar Timing for Mineral Operations & Almanac Completion")

=== Core Teaching

Lunar timing in the mineral work follows the same principles as in the vegetable
work, but with greater attention to the Moon's sign position, since mineral
processes are more sensitive to elemental character than most vegetable work.

*Moon in Earth signs (Taurus, Virgo, Capricorn)* for mineral work:
- Cohobation cycles: returning the dissolved mineral salt to the fixed body
- Crystallisation: encouraging the natural crystalline structure to form
- Calcination at moderate heat: fixing the volatile more completely into salt
- Any operation requiring the Salt principle to be strengthened

*Moon in Water signs (Cancer, Scorpio, Pisces)* for mineral work:
- Via Humida dissolutions: the Moon in a water sign supports the acid medium's
  dissolving action
- Extraction of the Mercury fraction: the watery Moon assists the volatile's
  release from the fixed matrix
- Beginning a new dissolution cycle after a rest period

*Moon in Fire signs (Aries, Leo, Sagittarius)* for mineral work:
- Calcination at higher temperatures
- Any operation requiring the Sulphur to be activated or burned off
- Initiating a new heating cycle in a preparation that has stalled

*Moon in Air signs (Gemini, Libra, Aquarius)* for mineral work:
- Distillation: the air sign supports the volatile rising
- Documentation and analysis sessions
- Comparative review of preparation stages

*Completing the Mineral Almanac.* The student now integrates all elements of
Month 5 into a complete mineral almanac: the multi-year framework (Saturn and
Jupiter cycles), the annual structure (solar ingresses, eclipses), the monthly
lunar phase and sign calendar, and the daily planetary hour schedule. This
almanac becomes a living document, consulted before every significant laboratory
action.

=== Topics This Week

- Lunar sign positions for mineral operations: earth, water, fire, air
- Completing the mineral almanac: integrating all timing levels
- The almanac as a living document: how to consult and update it

